#5703
the Thorn Cardinal Seredh~
@@Wthe Thorn Cardinal Seredh@@N~
@@WThorn Cardinal Seredh@@N stands precisely at the Sanctum's center, his posture demanding compliance from the architecture itself.
~
Thorn Cardinal Seredh brought military discipline and architectural intelligence to an institution that had previously relied on bureaucratic pressure alone. His central insight was ergonomic: if the only comfortable positions in a space are positions of submission, you do not need guards to enforce compliance â the body enforces it. His architectural plans, preserved in the wing's annotation halls, show precise measurements alongside clinical notes on how sustained physical discomfort degrades cognitive resistance and improves testimony quality. He established confession indexing by sin category rather than confessor identity, dispersing each person's complete record across dozens of files: controlled identity through fragmentation. He finds the Scriptorium's design satisfying in the way a craftsman finds good work satisfying, which is perhaps the most disturbing thing about him.
~
